  "prompt": "What are traditional British dishes?",
  "response": "Traditional British dishes encompass a variety of hearty and comforting foods that reflect the diverse culinary heritage of the UK. Here are some notable examples:\n\n1. **Fish and Chips**: Deep-fried battered fish served with chips (fries), often accompanied by tartar sauce and mushy peas.\n\n2. **Full English Breakfast**: A substantial breakfast typically consisting of eggs (fried or scrambled), bacon, sausages, baked beans, black pudding, tomatoes, and toast.\n\n3. **Shepherd's Pie**: A baked dish made with minced lamb topped with a layer of mashed potatoes.\n\n4. **Cottage Pie**: Similar to Shepherd's Pie, but made with minced beef instead of lamb.\n\n5. **Bangers and Mash**: Sausages served with mashed potatoes and usually accompanied by onion gravy.\n\n6. **Roast Beef and Yorkshire Pudding**: A traditional Sunday roast dish featuring juicy roast beef served with Yorkshire pudding, gravy, and vegetables.\n\n7. **Ploughman's Lunch**: A cold meal typically consisting of cheese, bread, pickles, and salad, often enjoyed in pubs.\n\n8. **Cornish Pasty**: A pastry filled with meat and vegetables, originally associated with Cornwall.\n\n9. **Steak and Kidney Pie**: A savory pie filled with diced steak, kidney (often from sheep or cattle), and gravy, encased in pastry.\n\n10. **Afternoon Tea**: A light meal/snack featuring tea served with finger sandwiches, scones with clotted cream and jam, and a selection of pastries.\n\n11. **Toad in the Hole**: Sausages baked in Yorkshire pudding batter, typically served with onion gravy.\n\n12. **Bubble and Squeak**: A dish made from leftover vegetables, usually potatoes and cabbage, pan-fried until crispy.\n\n13. **Sticky Toffee Pudding**: A rich dessert made from moist sponge cake, dates, and a sticky toffee sauce, often served with custard or ice cream.\n\n14. **Eton Mess**: A combination of crushed meringue, strawberries, and whipped cream, traditionally served at Eton College's annual cricket match.\n\nThese dishes are deeply rooted in British culture and continue to be enjoyed today in homes and restaurants across the UK.",
